# Procedural PHP, Tailwind CSS, and Apache/Nginx Routing Rules

You are assisting an expert PHP developer building a procedural PHP application with strict MVC-like separation of concerns. Do not invent new architectures, do not convert the project to OOP unnecessarily, and do not introduce external PHP frameworks.

## Environment Awareness
- **Local environment:** Development runs on `localhost` using **Apache**.
- **Live environment:** Production runs on **Nginx**.
- **Routing parity is required:** Any routing behavior implemented for Apache local development, including `.htaccess` rules, `mod_rewrite`, redirects, canonicalization, trailing-slash handling, front-controller rewrites, denied paths, and other URL behavior, must also be reflected in `deploy/nginx/app-routes.conf`.
- **Do not assume `.htaccess` works on production:** Nginx does not read `.htaccess` files, so Apache rewrite behavior must always be translated into the Nginx route config file.
- When creating, modifying, or suggesting any `.htaccess`, rewrite, redirect, or URL-routing logic, also update or provide the matching Nginx equivalent in `deploy/nginx/app-routes.conf`.
- If a rewrite or redirect rule is ambiguous, call it out explicitly and propose matching Apache and Nginx rules together.
-never change code outside of this project, only in the project folder lindon

## Core Separation of Concerns (MVC-like Boundaries)
- **Controllers (Orchestration):** Use procedural PHP files as front-controllers. They should only handle basic routing, receive input, call specific business logic functions, and include the view file.
- **Business Logic & Data:** Keep SQL queries completely out of views and mostly out of controllers. Make functions small, single-purpose, and store them in dedicated logic files. Introduce classes ONLY if they solve a very specific problem.
- **Views (Templates):** Keep business logic out of templates. Views must only loop through data provided by the controller and render HTML.

## Styling (Tailwind CSS Exclusively)
- **Tailwind Only:** Use ONLY Tailwind CSS utility classes for all styling, layout, typography, and responsive design directly in the view files.
- **Strict Prohibitions:** Do NOT write custom CSS in `<style>` tags. Do NOT create external `.css` files for component styling. Do NOT use Bootstrap, Foundation, or any other CSS framework under any circumstances.
- **Component Consistency:** When generating UI elements (like buttons, forms, or cards), reuse established Tailwind class combinations to maintain a consistent design system across the application.
-try to use the current branding and colors on the site where possible, unless asked to do otherwise

## Security & Best Practices
- **Escaping:** Always use the global `e()` helper function for output escaping in every single view. Context-aware output encoding is strictly required for untrusted data.
- **Bootstrapping:** Keep all application setup in one central `bootstrap.php` file (environment loading, DB connection, session starts, and shared includes). Do not duplicate setup code across different pages.

## Code Quality & Refactoring
- Write clean, maintainable procedural PHP. Keep it MVP-quality but highly extensible.
- When adding new features, actively look for and consolidate redundant logic or duplicate helpers instead of blindly appending new code.
- Treat Apache localhost routing and live Nginx routing as a paired concern whenever URL structure is affected.

